{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set split = card_data.split %}
{% set meta = card_data.meta %}
{% set alpha_mgr = (split | selectattr("role", "equalto", "alpha") | list)[0] %}
{% set hedge_mgr = (split | selectattr("role", "equalto", "hedge") | list)[0] %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/s5.css">
{% endblock %}

{% macro pct(x) %}{{ "%+.2f"|format(x * 100) }}%{% endmacro %}

{% macro manager_panel(m) %}
<article class="s5-manager s5-manager--{{ m.role }}" data-role="{{ m.role }}"
         data-cum-hedge="{{ m.cum_hedge | tojson }}"
         data-cum-alpha="{{ m.cum_alpha | tojson }}"
         data-borrow-dial="{{ m.borrow_dial | tojson }}">
  <header class="s5-manager__head">
    <h3 class="s5-manager__name">{{ m.name }}</h3>
    <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="{{ 'pos' if m.role == 'alpha' else 'neg' }}">
      {{ m.verdict }}</span>
  </header>
  <p class="s5-manager__hs">{{ m.hedge_share_gloss }}
    <span class="s5-manager__hs-note">(hedge share is descriptive — it convicts no one)</span></p>

  <div class="interval-stat" data-domain="short-alpha"
       data-lo="{{ m.net_ci[0] }}" data-point="{{ m.net_alpha_annual }}"
       data-hi="{{ m.net_ci[1] }}" data-gross="{{ m.gross_alpha_annual }}">
    <span class="interval-stat__label">Borrow-adjusted short alpha (90% interval)</span>
    <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ pct(m.net_alpha_annual) }}/yr</span>
    <div class="interval-stat__rail"><div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
      <div class="interval-stat__point"></div></div>
    <span class="interval-stat__range">net {{ pct(m.net_ci[0]) }} … {{ pct(m.net_ci[1]) }};
      gross {{ pct(m.gross_alpha_annual) }}, borrow drag
      &minus;{{ "%.2f"|format(m.borrow_drag_annual * 100) }}%/yr</span>
  </div>
  {% if m.fee_line %}<p class="s5-manager__feeline">{{ m.fee_line }}.</p>{% endif %}

  <svg class="s5-split-chart" viewBox="0 0 100 44" preserveAspectRatio="none" role="img"
       aria-label="Cumulative hedge component vs alpha component of the short sleeve"></svg>

  <div class="s5-dial" data-dial="{{ m.role }}">
    <span class="s5-dial__label">Borrow fee assumption (skepticism dial, 0–5%/yr)</span>
    <input type="range" class="s5-dial__range" min="0" max="{{ m.borrow_dial | length - 1 }}"
           value="{{ (meta.borrow_cost_annual / 0.005) | int }}" step="1"
           aria-label="borrow fee assumption">
    <p class="s5-dial__readout" data-dial-readout></p>
  </div>
</article>
{% endmacro %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="s5-intro">
  <div class="badge-row"><span class="tier-badge" data-tier="P">P · measured</span></div>
  <p class="s5-headline">
    Two synthetic long/short mandates — <strong>Saxbridge Capital</strong> and
    <strong>Drybrook Capital</strong> — run identical structures ({{ "%.0f"|format(meta.gross * 100) }}
    gross / {{ "%.0f"|format(meta.net * 100) }} net, {{ meta.n_long }} longs, {{ meta.n_short }} shorts,
    same long-side skill). Both short sleeves are ~80% hedge by variance. The entire fee-relevant
    difference lives in the borrow-adjusted residual — which only an interval-reported,
    borrow-adjusted decomposition surfaces.
  </p>
</section>

<aside class="s5-guide" aria-label="What this exhibit shows">
  <h2 class="s5-guide__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <div class="s5-guide__block">
    <h3 class="s5-guide__subtitle">What you are looking at</h3>
    <p>The short sleeve's monthly P&amp;L split into a <strong>hedge component</strong> (measured
      factor exposure × factor returns) and an <strong>alpha component</strong> (weights ×
      idiosyncratic moves). At tier P this split is an exact identity — accounting, not
      estimation. Saxbridge's alpha line grinds upward; Drybrook's wanders around zero, while
      both hedge lines swing with the market.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="s5-guide__block">
    <h3 class="s5-guide__subtitle">How to read it</h3>
    <ul class="s5-guide__list">
      <li><strong>The hedge share</strong> is descriptive — ~80% in both books — so it convicts
        no one; hedging is what shorts are structurally for.</li>
      <li><strong>The borrow-adjusted alpha rail</strong> is the number the verdict reads from:
        the point net of borrow, the band its 90% interval, with a tick for the gross.</li>
      <li><strong>The borrow dial</strong> sweeps the flat fee across 0–5%/yr — drag it and watch
        Drybrook stay negative and Saxbridge stay positive.</li>
      <li><strong>The hit-rate power gate</strong> renders the clustered t at the full window and
        refuses at half — the trade count, not the manager, is the binding constraint.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The full methodology is in the
      <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">method spec</a>.</p>
  </div>
</aside>

<section class="s5-split">
  {{ manager_panel(alpha_mgr) }}
  {{ manager_panel(hedge_mgr) }}
</section>

<section class="s5-gate">
  <h2 class="s5-gate__title">Short-side hit rate — power-gated</h2>
  <p class="s5-window">The demo window is ten years ({{ meta.months }} months),
    <strong>deliberately generous</strong>: even with a decade of positions the hit-rate
    certification barely clears ({{ alpha_mgr.hit_full.trades }} round trips vs the
    ~{{ meta.short_trade_gate }}-trade line), and at a realistic five-year window the gate refuses.</p>
  <div class="s5-gate__toggle">
    {% for m in split %}
    <div class="s5-gate__row" data-role="{{ m.role }}">
      <span class="s5-gate__name">{{ m.name }}</span>
      <span class="s5-gate__full">T={{ meta.months }}: hit rate
        {{ "%.1f"|format(m.hit_full.hit_rate * 100) }}% (t = {{ "%+.2f"|format(m.hit_full.hit_t) }},
        {{ m.hit_full.trades }} round trips)</span>
      <span class="s5-gate__marginal">{{ m.hit_full.trades }} of ~{{ m.hit_full.gate }} — below the certification line</span>
      <div class="power-gate s5-gate__reduced">
        <span class="power-gate__title">power gate · T={{ meta.toggle_months }}</span>
        <p class="power-gate__reason">Insufficient N ({{ m.hit_reduced.trades }} round trips;
          gate ~{{ m.hit_reduced.gate }}) — the number is refused, not shown. A five-year window
          of a {{ meta.n_short }}-name sleeve is lucky-draw territory.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
</section>

<section class="s5-tiers">
  <h2 class="s5-tiers__title">What each tier buys</h2>
  <div class="s5-tier" data-tier-panel="E">
    <span class="tier-badge" data-tier="E">E · exposure summaries</span>
    <p>Factor split only: the measured short-sleeve exposure path and the reconstructed hedge
      component. <strong>No alpha estimate</strong> — the residual is unobservable at E, and the
      panel says so.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="s5-tier" data-tier-panel="R">
    <span class="tier-badge" data-tier="R">R · returns only</span>
    <p>Refusal: short-book attribution requires disclosed sleeve returns or positions; a blended
      long/short return does not identify its sleeves. <em>Exception:</em> a manager-disclosed
      short-sleeve series runs the constant-beta factor regression, chipped
      <span class="verdict-chip" data-verdict="neutral">manager-disclosed attribution</span>
      (R² {{ "%.2f"|format(alpha_mgr.r_disclosed.r2) }} / {{ "%.2f"|format(hedge_mgr.r_disclosed.r2) }}
      stands in for the hedge share) — with the timing-leak caveat: a constant-beta regression
      cannot separate selection alpha from hedge timing.</p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The sleeve's P&amp;L is its measured exposures times the factor returns, plus its weights times
the idiosyncratic surprises — given positions and a factor model, an exact identity (§3.3). The
hedge share is a ratio of measured quantities and carries no significance claim. Gross short alpha
is 12 × the mean alpha component; its 90% interval is the S2 tear-sheet machinery (Newey–West HAC
cross-checked against a block bootstrap, widened to the looser of the two) applied to the alpha
series — never a bare OLS SE. Borrow enters as a deterministic level, not a regression term: the
fee bill is a known cost, not a priced risk.</p>
<p>The short-side hit rate is the active batting average — a short wins when its name underperforms
the month's cross-section — tested month-clustered against 50%, because positions within a month
co-move. Power is the binding constraint: detecting a 55% hit rate at 80% power needs ~780
independent trades, and a 25-name quarter-turnover sleeve accumulates only 745 in a decade — which
is why the gate refuses at five years and this card ships one calibrated statement per sleeve, not a
persistence ranking.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/s5-shortbook.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
